column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, BAX Global, Inc. discovered a release inside the trailer. Upon investigation, it was determined that the lids had come loose on three (3) of 164 plastic jerricans, containing potassium hydroxide solution.  Apparently the release was due to improper packaging by PPG Industries, the shipper of the product.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel performed cleanup using gloves and absorbents to contain the release and placed the damaged jerricans, along with the cleanup debris into recovery drums.   PPG Industries, Inc. will coordinate disposal of all waste generated, in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures  reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to improper shipper packaging, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, BAX Global Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: While in the railyard, ETCX 421036 (DOT 111A100W6 tank car) was reported emanating a residue product odor. ETCX 421036 was cordoned-off in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were called to inspect ETCX 421036 and eliminate the chemical odor source. The responders removed seal numbered 006598 from the housing cover and inspected all valves and fittings. All valves were in the closed position, but the vapor line closure plug was found to be finger loose. One of the responders tool tightened this loose closure plug and the vinegar type odor ceased. Response was concluded by 1908 hrs. CDT, 10/07/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE, WITH NOT MORE THAN 0.2%  OF COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS, INCLUDING ANY ORGANIC SUBSTANCE CALCULATED AS CARBON TO THE EXCLUSION OF ANY OTHER ADDED SUBSTANCE
column168: An Austin Powder Company tanker and tractor where heading westbound on Highway 29. The tanker rolled over along the highway causing the tanker to release about 8,000 lbs. of Ammonium Nitrate. Austin Powder Company contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) to manage the site of the spill.  ERTS contacted a local contractor to clean and remediate the spill.  ERTS reported to the Texas CEQ and was given report number 2008-3628 as well as the NRC and it was assigned report number 886031. Contractor arrived on site about one hour after the call and removed the tanker and they attempted to reclaim as much product as possible and to clean the site with any leftover waste.  They containerize the reclaimed ammonium nitrate under the supervision of Austin Powder, approximately 1,000 lbs. still needed to be disposed of and was.  The contaminated soil was removed and disposed of properly and backfilled.

A Quality Carriers Tanker and Tractor rolled over along Highway I-95.  There was a minor leak which resulted in less than a gallon of the product.  ERTS was called in to manage the response and did so by contacting a contractor.  THe product was transferred to another tanker, the tanker involved in the incident was removed from the site and the spill was cleaned up by the contractors and disposed of properly.

column168: On October 8, 2008 at 17:04, personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered PPGX1829, a residue tank car of Chlorine leaking from top of the car and chlorine-like odor in the vicinity of the car. The car was isolated and shipper, local, state and first responder agencies were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2008-10-08-00226). Veolia Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene along with a CSXT Hazardous Material Systems Field Manager. Veolia and CSXT personne found the A-end Liquid line closure plug less than tool tight and the valve not fully closed.  Contractor personnel re-seated and secured the valve and secured the plug. Contractors decontaminated the interior of the protective dome housing and hand holds. The leak was secured and the car is held in bad order status until car owner has an opportunity to inspect and fully prepare car for transportation. This incident did require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 300  NARRI:  2(4+10+0) X (2+0) = 56

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to NYK Line as non-hazardous cargo by OOCL USA, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the NYK Line container vessel Bellavia V. 16W42 from Jersey City, NJ to Hong Kong, China.    OOCL advised NYK Line after the vessel had sailed from New Jersey of the following hazardous materials in the container that were not originally booked or otherwise identified.    - UN1604, ETHYLENEDIAMINE, CL 3, PG II, F/P +34C  - UN1268, PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. (NAPTHA), CL 3, PG 2, F/P +14C    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the hazardous item.    OOCL subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to NYK Line.

column168: Two BNSF train crew members reported a chemical odor emanating from standing rail cars in the railyard. All BNSF employees working in the railyard were moved upwind and away from the chemical odor. The local F.D. was called and their inspection for the possible odor source resulted in no findings. BNSF contractors also inspected rail cars in the railyard for the odor source. Responders reported GLNX 3038 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) as the odor source. A detailed inspection under the valve housing cover after intact seal numbered TBS 299735 was removed, revealed that the chained liquid valve handle (that was removed from the valve assembly) had wedged itself between the liquid valve body and the top of the vacuum relief valve (VRV); which actuated the VRV producing the residue product odor. The valve handle was moved and repositioned within the valve housing area; and the product odor ceased. Afterwards, air monitoring verified no measurable vapor release. No free liquid product was evident. The valve housing cover was closed and resealed with seal numbered SRS 000184. Response was concluded by 1630 hrs. CDT, 10/10/08.  GLNX 3038's side specification stencil displayed the last tank qualification in the year of 1999 and next due in 2009.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF train crew reported entrained GATX 62590 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) with a small vapor cloud emanating from the top of this tank car after arrival in the railyard. GATX 62590 was cordoned-off awaiting inspection from a BNSF contract responder. No vapor cloud was observed after GATX 62590 remained motionless. The contract responder inspected GATX 62590 and reported finding the frangible disc housing's top closure cap not applied and the frangible disc missing. Also, a portion (approx. 1/3) of the hard plastic threaded base for securing the top closure cap had broken off. The responder did not have a suitable replacement disc and the shipper arranged for another contractor to bring in a suitable 165 psi replacement frangible disc. The new 165 psi frangible disc was installed. No free liquid product was observed on the tank car shell, only a small dried residue stain. No ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 1530 hrs. CDT, 10/12/08.

column168: We received the shipment and performed a document inspection, as per usual procedures.  The shipper declared that the shipment was non-hazardous, despite the fact that the documentation stated UN1993, Flammable Liquid.  We had the shipper complete a shippers certification of articles not restricted.  The shipper indicated a flash point of 53 degrees F.  We contacted Michelle Jackson (310-725-3741) of the FAA, and they promptly came to our facility and performed a further inspection.  In fact, the shipment is hazardous materials.
column169: In this case, prior training to identify hazardous materials was responsible for catching this shipment.  No changes are planned, except that we will continue to keep our training programs up-to-date.

column168: We received the shipment and performed a documentation inspection as usual.  The shipper had provided two shippers declarations for hazardous goods, both with different dates, but for the same commodity (ID8000).  We then proceeded to perform a packaging inspection, where it was found that the carton was not labeled correctly.  We contacted the shipper and were told that the shipment should be exported as usual.  We then contacted the hazmat packer that was hired by the shipper. The hazmat packer was suspicious because the box that they had packed was not the one we were describing.  The hazmat packer came to our facility and confirmed that the package was different.  We then contacted Michelle Jackson of the FAA (310-725-3741).  The FAA came out and inspected the cartons, where it was discovered that the package contained several 1 qt. cans of paint.  The commercial invoices had declared 2 cans of spray paint and some battery cleaners.  No spray paint or battery cleaners where found in the carton.
column169: Our training is what caught this shipment.  Therefore, we will not make any adjustments, except to keep our employee training up-to-date.

column168: On Monday 10/20/08 @ 1:15 PM after loading trailer number 502256 with LPA 142 solvent, the Normal Paraffin Unit Loader discovered a dripping leak from the bottom valve area of the trailer.  A transport company mechanic was called to make repairs to the bottom valve, but it was discovered during closer inspection that the tank shell was cracked.  The trailer was unloaded and sent back to the transport company for repairs.  The leaking container was inside the curbed area during the entire incident.

On October 13, 2008 at 06:10, a car inspector reported a loud hissing noise while inspecting #8 departure track at the CSXT Selkirk Yard. GATX 20498, a loaded Carbon Dioxide tank car, was found venting from the top of the car. The car was moved to an isolated track area, and CHEMTREC was notified (report #20081013-00050) to contact the shipper. A CSXT HazMat Sentinel investigated and found the rupture disc had blown and was venting. On October 15, 2008, the shipper sent a technical representative to Selkirk Yard and replaced the rupture disc. No cause was determined for the failure of the rupture disc.    NOTE:  A special switching move was required.  NOTE:  An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not required for this incident.    Cause Code:  441  NARR:  2 (5+1+)) x (3+0) = 36

column168: On October 14, 2008 at 08:30, personnel in the CSXT Howell Yard discovered GATX 48501, a residue tank car of Anhydrous Ammonia, leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, local, and state agencies as applicable were notified (CHEMTREC Report# - 2008-10-14-00086). Summit Contracting and Hulcher Services, both CSXT response contractors, were dispatched to the scene and found that the pressure relief device leaking vapors. Contractor personnel relieved pressure from the car through an air sparging process into water. The car was secured for later repair by the shippers' qualified tank car contractor to replace the pressure relief valve.     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  414  NARRI:  2 (4+9+0) x (2+0) = 52

column168: On October 6, 2008 at 17:15, a CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager was notified by FRA Hazmat Inspector Matsinger that GATX 70260, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid N.O.S. (Flux), waqs observed leaking from the top of the car at the CSXT Curtis Bay Yard . The car was isolated and the shipper was notified. A CSXT Hazardous Materials Manager responded and met the FRA Inspectors to determine source of leak. The leak appeared to be a gasket leaking on either a four bolt blind flange or the four bolt liquid line flanges. Working through EMI, Safety Kleen contacted Specialized Professional Services as a Certified Class G Tank Car Facility to respond to find source of leak and repair. SPSI personnel were unable to determine the exact source of the leak due to solidification of the Flux. SPSI cleaned spilled material from tank car. CSXT Hazardous Materials advised EMI that Safety Kleen would have to secure an FRA movement approval to move the car approximately one mile to the consignee to be off loaded and then sent to home shop for repair.     NOTE:  An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  NOTE:  This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 279  NARRI:  2 (5+1+0) X (2+0) = 24

column168: FURX 130282 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported dripping liquid from the bottom outlet valve (BOV) while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected FURX 130282. Inspection by the responder revealed that the bottom operated BOV was in the closed position and the primary bottom outlet cap (BOC) was tool tight. The responder cycled the BOV operating handle which slowed the product drips emanating from around the BOC. The responder then removed the BOV operating handle to observe the valve stem closure position, which indicated that the valve was not being fully closed with the operating handle in the closed position. The responder corrected this alignment which enabled the BOV to be fully closed. Once, the BOV was closed, the responder removed the BOC to inspect the BOC gasket. Loose sediment was found atop the BOC gasket which prevented a good quality gasket seal. The inner BOC was cleaned, the gasket was wiped and flipped over; and the BOC was reapplied and tool tightened. Afterwards, (approx. 1745 hrs. PDT, 10/17/08) no further product dripping was observed. All spillage evaporated. Intact seals removed from the top valve housing cover and the BOV were CGL BLAIR 0240257 and 0240258 respectively. FURX 130282's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2007.

A box truck containing hazardous waste was en route between the shipper's location and the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility where the contents of the vehicle were transferred onto a second vehicle for continuing transportation.  during the transfer operation, a small amout of liquid was released from the top closure of 2 of the containers resulting in an aggregate reelase amount of approximatley 1 pint.  The material was contained on the floor of the van trailer and it was immedialtey absorbed with speedii dry and placed in the container for disposal.  The cause of the release was attributed to a damaged gasket on one container and a missing gasket on a second.  Facility personnel replaced both gaskets and secured the containers for continuing transportation.
column169: During the loading operation, the driver did not identify and issue withthe containers as they were loaded.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver has been re-instructed to continue to inspect each container and take appropriate corrective actins should a damaged or suspect container be identified.  In addition, the shipper has been infomred of the incident and asdvised to ensure each container is secured and closed in such a way to preclude a release of material.

column168: UTLX 206487 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 206487 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting inspection. BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Material responded and inspected UTLX 206487. The responder found 4 of 8 manway securement bolts finger loose. No issues were found when the manway gasket was inspected. The responder secured the manway cover by properly tool tightening all manway securement bolts using the star pattern tightening process. All spillage was confined to the shell of UTLX 206487 and was wiped. No ground impact was evident. Response was concluded by 0145 hrs. CDT, 10/22/08. Intact seals removed from the manway cover were CRRM 061617 and 17693. They were replaced by BNSF seal BNSF 1247.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Shipment of 31 pieces of Food items tendered.  Shipment was x-rayed for security reasons and 28 pounds of undisclosed hasmat found in the shipment.  Jeff Dietz (FAA)was called and he responded.  The 28 pounds of hazmat removed from shipment and the rest of the shipment released for transport.  Shipper called to retrieve the 28 pounds of hazmat.
column169: Shipper needs to have more training on what a hazmat is.

column168: A BNSF mechanical carman working in the railyard (receiving yard) reported a chemical odor emanating from rail cars that had previously arrived from an inbound BNSF train. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and immediately started to inspect rail cars for the odor source. The responder reported DBCX 200142 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) emanating a product odor and a liquid stain that originated from under the valve housing cover was observed. DBCX 200142's valve housing cover with intact seal was opened for valve and fitting inspection. The responder found the one inch threaded sample line valve was loose at its threaded connection into the tank car. This was tool tightened. Also, all the mounting flange bolt nuts for the liquid and vapor valves were loose at the base of these valves. These were all tool tightened (8-10 nuts on each valve flange). The liquid and vapor valves packing retainer nuts on the valve stems were also loose and these were tool tightened. All valves were in the closed position. The responder noted that these valves appeared to be recently installed. Non-evaporated spillage around the valve housing was wiped and afterwards no product odor was evident. DBCX 200142 was released to proceed to its destination at 2340 hrs. PDT, 10/15/08. No further exceptions were noted during subsequent movements in the railyard of DBCX 200142.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Driver #1 did not carry out all of established company job procedure by failing to realign tank valves after he finishedhis back gauge unload. Driver # 2 failed to follow established company unload procedures by not hand gauging tanks prior to unloading, he only looked at the external gauge on the isolated tank assuming that the valves were properlyaligned and both unload tanks were pumped down. Driver # 3 did not follow established company unload procedures bynot hand gauging tanks prior to unloading, he only looked at the external gauge on the isolated tank assuming that thevalves were properly aligned and both unload tanks were pumped down, he also violated the established company jobprocedure by not remaining at the controls of the pump outside of the truck during the unloading process. Crude oil wascontained within the dike.
column169: Eliminate back gauging of frac/test tank loads so there is no need to isolate tanks by changing the tank valve alignments.Insure there are overfill bypass lines between installed between tanks at all unload stations. Install external tanks gauges.Look at more strict reprimands for job/procedure behavior rather than waiting on reprimanding the results.

ERTS dispatched a contractor to the site to assist in the event that a transfer was required or a release occurred.  Once the container had been determined safe to relocate, an additional trailer was brought to the site and the container loaded on the trailer bed.      Initially I was informed that no evacuation would be required unless a transfer took place however it was brought to my attention later that an evacuation had been implemented by the fire department.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was en route from the shipper's location to Clean Harbor's Braintree, MA hazardous waste transfer, storage and disposal facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of containerized hazardous waste onto an alternate van trailer for continuing transportation.  During the transfer operation, a 55 gallon container was identified as having a small pinhole leak near the bottom chime of the container allowing approximately 1 gallon of material to escape from the package onto the floor of the van trailer and the concrete truck pad where the vehicle was staged.  Facility personnel immediately donned approppriate personal protective equipment  and proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum.  Speedi dry was used to contain and absorbe all free liquids that were released from the package.  This material along with all clean-up debris was placed in the salvage drum which was secured and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time of loading, all contianers were inspected and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed or identified by the driver loading the vehicle.  The driver has been re-instructed to insure that should a pre-loading inspection identify a container of questinable integrity that all actions necessary to secure and recontainerize the package be done before accepting for transportation.

column168: A van trailer containing hazadous waste was en route from the shipper's location to Clean Harbors Laurel, MD facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities of hazards waste for continuing transportation. column168: Railcar was under air pressure while unloading. Car was approximately 90% unloaded when the 7 inch gasket inside of the unload valve failed and allowed a small amount(approximately 10 gallons)to escape from the top unloading valve. The emergency air controlled valve was activated from the ground to close the valve and stop the leak. Chemtrade Logistics was contacted to call RESCAR to do a permanent repair. After 3 tries and 2 different gasket sizes, RESCAR decided that they could not do a permanent repair on site. They then tagged the car as going to the HOME/SHOP and Industrial Chemicals was able to remove the balance of the product from the car using minimal air pressure with no further leaks. Chemtrade Logistics was contacted to get a FRA approval for movement of the car and they have initiated that process. The 10 gallons of sulfuric acid 93% released from the railcar was neutralized and collected for disposal.
This undeclared HAZMAT was discovered by US Customs & Border Protection during inspection of import cargo.  No release or damage.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While travelling on Highway 101 North, the back tires of the tractor caught on fire, causing damage to the shipment. The San Jose Fire Department and the California Highway Patrol responded to assess the site.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. of San Jose, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. applied absorbent material as needed and placed the damaged containers into over-pack drums.  Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Maumee Express, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: A van trailer containing non regulated waste collected from homeowners was being delivered to the intended waste management facility.  Upon arrival at the facility, it was discovereed that a UN11G boc containing paint related material had released approximatley 5 gallons of pait from the package.  Facilty personnel immedialtely contained the release and initiated response activities.  A suitable absorbent material was used to absorb all free liquids.  All debris generated from the response activities was containerized and processed at the facility.  Upon inspection, it was determined that several cans of paint within the package had not been packed in an upright position allowing pait to escaped from the package.  All material was recieved and processed at this faciltiy as it was the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the container was loaded, the driver did not identify any issues with the package. In additon, the individuals repsonsible for loading this container have been advised to insure that all paint cans are packaged in an upright position to prevent an inadvertant release.

column168: A CMC Railroad employee reported exposure from a vapor mist that emanated from GATX 32749 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) while this tank car was in the railyard. The employee immediately cleansed and returned to work without a request for medical observation or assistance. GATX 32749 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting an inspection from BNSF contract responders that were summoned. The contract responders inspected GATX 32749 and reported finding the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. The responders replaced the frangible disc in kind. Product spillage on the side shell of GATX 32749 was neutralized and wiped. A small amount of liquid product that dripped atop the ground and onto a railroad crosstie was also neutralized.

column168: A BNSF intermodal hub employee reported intermodal container UETU 207025 dripping an unknown liquid substance onto the asphalt pavement in the intermodal parking lot. UETU 207025 was destined for overseas export to South Korea. The area around UETU 207025 was cordoned off awaiting inspection from a response contractor. The contractor reported that the lading consisted of double stacked palletized and poly wrapped 55 gallon steel drums. No rear end bracing was present, but the lading was stowed tightly against the container's sidewalls and against the rear doors, which left little room for rear bracing. One drum towards the rear of the container was found to be the leak source. This compromised drum had a small crack at the bottom drum ring, possibly from contact with another drum, the container's interior sidewall or damaged prior to or during loading. Other drums inside this container were noted with dents in the drum bodies, but none of these were compromised. The leaking drum was placed inside an 85 gallon recovery drum and returned to the lading after the interior of UETU 207025 was cleaned. The spillage on the outside of UETU 207025 was cleaned along with the ground impact area. Soiled cleaning materials were placed into a disposal drum for appropriate future disposal. Response was concluded at 2200 hrs. PDT, 10/20/08.
column169: No additional comments.

column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported a chemical odor emanating from a track of standing rail cars in the railyard. This area in the railyard was cordoned off and rail operations were suspended. A nearby BNSF contract environmental responder investigated the odor source and determined that the source of the odor was amongst seven residue tank cars coupled together that last contained methyl mercaptan. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder arrived and inspected these suspect tank cars. The BNSF responder reported finding ACFX 94864 (DOT 105J300W tank car) leaking residue product vapor from the vapor valve stem with a loose packing retainer nut. The responder tightened this retainer nut by 1610 hrs. CDT, 10/23/08 stopping the vapor leak. Another team of BNSF contract responders using a Photo Ionization Detector (PID) performed inspections and monitoring of all these tank cars finding no other securement deficiencies and no further vapor leaks or odor. Response was concluded by 1740 hrs. CDT and rail operations were resumed at 1750 hrs. CDT, 10/23/08.  The specification stencil on the side of ACFX 94864 portrayed the last tank qualification in the year 2003 and next due in 2013.  The intact seal removed from the ACFX 94864's valve housing cover was EVONIK 0042242 and it was replaced with BNSF seal numbered 174113.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 10/12/2008 at 12:50, personnel in the CSXT AACA yard discovered NATX 300638, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., with a slosh leak from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Poet Biorefining was notified. Hepaco, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found 1 manway bolt less than tool tight and the manway gasket was the wrong size. Hepaco replace the manway gasket with a boot style gasket and made all manway bolts tool tigh. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. No special movements were made with this car.    NOTE: An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  NOTE:  This incident did not require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 211  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 15th, 2008, at 11:58, personnel in the CSXT Framingham Yard discovered GATX 300752, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide Solution (UN 1814), leaking from the top of the tank car. GATX 300752 was moved to an isolated track and Ashta Chemicals was notified via Chemtrec (report 2008-10-15-00073). A CSXT response contractor, Global Remediation Services, was called to respond. Global personne found three of six manway bolts less than tool tight. Global inspected the manway gasket, re-secured the bolts on the manway and the tank car was decontaminated. GATX 300752 was released for disposition.    An (AAR QA Program) 7.1 Non-conformance Report was not required for this incident.    Note: GATX 300752 was moved from the outbound local to an isolated track in Framingham Yard - this did require a special move.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On October 17, 2008, 10:00, CSXT personnel discovered GATX 300752, a loaded tank car of Potassium Hydroxide Solution (UN 1814), leaking from the top of the tank car while being switched at Taunton, MA. A CSXT Trainmaster contacted the consignee, Borden + Remington in Fall River, MA, to respond and investigate.  Borden + Remington personnel found that the Rupture/Frangible disc was blown and they replaced the disc and decontaminated the top of the tank car. GATX 300752 was released for delivery.    An (AAR QA Program) 7.1 Non-conformance Report was not required for this incident.    Note: GATX 300752 had no special move associated with this incident.  Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 40

column168: FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector S. Hoose, noted the 2" bottom outlet plug loose and product adhering to the lower tank jacket and 6" outlet cap of tank car UTLX 631045(R/ SODIUM HYDROXIDE) while inspecting rail cars in the CN Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL. All appropriate departments notified. CN Hazmat Team and Shipper responded, noting the 6" bottom outlet cap and 2" auxiliary valve plug less than tool tight which allowed a small amount of product between the closed bottom outlet valve and auxiliary valve to be released. 6" cap threads cleaned and secured, auxiliary plug secured. Tank car jacket deconned.  Mr Hoose also noted the 1" air/vapor line valve plug loose and a small amount of product residue from off loading under the protective housing. Shipper corrected. Tank car released for movement.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from a shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver was forced to execute a hard braking maneuver that resulted in a 250 gallon IBC to slide forward into a pallet jack puncturing the side wall of the container.  The driver immediately pulled into a parking area where he inspected the cargo portion of the vehicle and discovered that approximately 150 gallons of material had escaped from the package onto the floor of the box truck.  The driver immediately secured the vehicle and initiated the spill response plan which included applying an absorbent material on the ground to protect the spread of material.  Once secured, the driver called his dispatcher who dispatched a response crew to the scene.  Calls were made to local police, fire and regulatory agencies advising them of the situation.  Upon arrival, local emergency personnel monitored the scene as the emergency response crew initiated the spill clean-up efforts which entailed absorbing all free liquids with a suitable absorbent material, containerizing all cleanup debris and transferring the material that remained in the damaged IBC into a suitable container.  In addition, the response crew decontaminated the cargo area and reloaded the containers for continuing transportation.  All material generated as a result of this incident was sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT.  NOTE: THIS IS A DUPLICATE REPORT OF E-2008110006 TRACKING NUMBER 460616.  A box truck, proceeding from the point of pickup to the intended waste disposal facility, braked hard in traffic, causing a 250gl tote to shift forward in the  load, striking a pallet jack. A puncture hole occurred in the tote caused by the handle of the pallet jack. The driver immediately pulled off of the road into  a parking lot, donned the appropriate PPE and contained the spill with absorbent material in his spill kit. The police, fire, Illinois Department of  Transportation (report#20081573), and Clean Harbors emergency response team were all immediately notified. The Police and Fire Depts arrived on the  scene but did not participate in the clean up. The emergency response personnel cleaned up the spill with the appropriate absorbent material, packing it  into drums and cleaning up the pavement where the spill had been contained. There were no waterways or drains affected. The truck was loaded with all  cleanup materials and continued to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: REPORT 1  It was determined that the driver of the vehicle failed to adequately secure and position the materials accepted for transportation.  The driver has been retrained to insure that proper and effective blocking and bracing techniques are used for all future shipments and the devices used must be able to prevent any movement during normal traffic conditions which include hard braking events.  This is to include any supplies and/or equipment carried in the cargo potion of the vehicle.  In addition, the driver has been made aware that a repeat event will result in appropriate disciplinary action.    SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT  All parties involved in the loading of the truck were retrained in proper loading and securing of all items in the vehicle. Upon departure, the driver had  secured the pallet jack and the totes, but it was inadequate for the shifting of the load which subsequently occurred.

column168: On 10/22/08 at approximately 1230 PM IMTT-Bayonne operators were loading methanol into a truck at designated loading rack when, approximately 3/4 through the load, the operator noticed a drip under the tanker compartment.  The operator immediately shut down the operation, secured the truck and put a bucket under the tanker compartment to collect the dripping product.  The truck was then moved to a secured containment area and another tanker truck was used to pump off approximately 5,000 gallons of methanol.  The new truck was then sent back to the loading rack and the operation resumed without further incident.  Upon further examination it was discovered that the leak occurred at an existing 2" weld on the bottom of the tanker compartment just in front of the rear axel.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product involved to inform them of the incident.  The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with tank truck and related components to prevent recurrences.

This railcar was observed venting at Geismar yard after being switched into a track.  Upon closer inspection, the SRV inspection cap, retainer ring, rupture disk, and surge protection were missing. column168: Driver arrived at customer destination, checked in and proceeded to unloading station. He hooked up and started the unloading process which included applying air presure to push the load out of the trailer. The unloading was only in process a few minutes, driver stated he had only 5 lbs of air pressure in the tank, when the tank ruptured in the shell on the right side of the trailer, approximately half way up the side below the dome lid area. Driver immediately shut down the air pressure and went through the air bleed off process to relieve the pressure in the tank, but the tank continued to drain off until it reached the level of the rupture. Plant employees and the driver responded to the situation by connecting a pump to the discharge line and pumped the product down. Soda ash was put down to neutralize the product. Plant management made arrangements with a clean-up company to clean up the spill.
column169: Failure of the tank wall is being inspected and verified by a third party facility to determine cause.

React, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the 2" continuous vent carbon filter was leaking. Contractor personnel replaced the carbon filter, decontaminated the car and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move and does not require an AAR 7.1.    Cause Code: 439  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

AWB#-MVW 29238656753 SDM    ON 10/05/2008 AT 1009, A LEAKING AND ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "A" BUILDING, LOCATED AT THE DHL MAIN SORT FACILITY, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  SPILL TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES AND WILLIAM HENDERSON DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A FLAMMABLE ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN RACING PARTS, INK CARTRIDGES AND 2 X 1 GALLON METAL CANS OF PERFORMANCE EPOXY.  DUE TO NO POSITIVRE MEANS OF CLOSURE ON 1 OF THE METAL CANS, A TOTAL OF 1 GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #417, N792AX.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.    THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WE ALSO RECEIVED A STATEMENT FROM THE SHIPPER INDICATING THAT THE MATERIAL INSIDE OF THE 2 METAL CANS MARKED PERFORMANCE EPOXY WERE NOT WHAT THE CANS CONTAINED.  THE ACTUAL PRODUCT INSIDE OF THE METAL CANS CONTAINED MOLD RELEASE.  THE FAA DID INSPECT THIS AND WILL CONTINUE TO DO FOLLOW UP FOR MORE INFORMATION.    CLEAR OF SCENE:  1048.    THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was loading gasoline at a loading terminal, preparing to deliver to a client location. When finished loading compartments 1 and 5, the riser did not shut of when it was supposed to. The probe activated but did not stop the electricity to the pump and the gas continued to flow. The dirver immediately pulled the emergency stop and requested assistance. It is estimated that between 250 and 300 gallons of gas were spilled. Two, on-call employees from colonial arrived at the scene. They shut down that lane at the terminal and inspected the meter, it read "valve fault overrun production". Upon inspection it was determined that there had been a faulty valve. The operations center would have the problem in that lane fixed by morning. Colonial took repsonsibility for the spill and cleanup. No product ever reached soil or drains.
column169: Faulty valve was determined to have been the cause of spill. The loading terminal corrected problem.

column168: The BNSF yardmaster reported TILX 192826 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was leaking a small amount of product from the top fitting area during movement in the railyard. No active release was observed when TILX 192826 remained motionless. TILX 192826 was cordoned off in the railyard. A BNSF response contractor was called to inspect TILX 192826. This inspection revealed product wetness around the manway nozzle. The manway securement bolts were found to be tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected, repositioned and the manway cover resecured. Subsequent rail movement of TILX 192826 within the railyard observed by the contract responders revealed a small product release visible at the manway cover during movement. The responders concluded that the manway gasket was not sealing properly. The shipper was notified and a shipper responder with a new manway gasket was dispatched. The shipper responder replaced the manway gasket, resecured the manway cover and applied new seals. Response was concluded by approximately Noon CDT, 10/28/08. The removed gasket had the appearance of gasket compression inconsistencies on a portion of this gasket. After the securement was completed, subsequent movements of TILX 192826 in the railyard revealed no further product release. No ground impact was evident and non-wiped spillage on the tank shell evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: During switching operations in the railyard, CMC Railroad employees reported GATX 4687 (DOT 111A100W5 tank car) with a product expulsion from the top of this tank car. No product release was observed when GATX 4687 remained motionless. GATX 4687 was cordoned off in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders inspected GATX 4687 and reported that the 165 psi frangible disc had ruptured. The responders applied a stainless steel frangible disc on a temporary basis until a proper non-metallic frangible disc could be procured. Spillage on the tank shell was neutralized and wiped. No ground impact was evident. The appropriate 165 psi frangible disc was applied by 1630 hrs. CDT, 10/29/08.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous materials was en route from the shipper's location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle stopped at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility located in San Jose California for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities for continuing transportation.  During the movement of a 55 gallon non-bulk package, approximatley 6 ounces of material was released from the package onto the gloves of the undividual moving the container.  The individual immedialtely secured the container and obtained assistance in placing the container into a suitable salvage drum.  This was accomplished and the container was placed onto the vehicle for continuing traportation.  Prior to securing the container, an inspection was conducted and a small slit was idneitifed near the top of the container.  It is beleived that during transport, this drum was cut by other freight resulting in this damage.
column169: At the time the vehicle was loadied, the container was inspected and no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, drivers will be reminded to ensure a thorough inspection of each container is made prior to loading and should a container of questionable integrity be identified, appropriate corrective actions are taken before acceptance.  In addition, drivers will be reminded to insure the truck is free of any sharp objects that could compromise the structural integrtiy of a container once loading in the vehicel.

column25: Maersk Inc. for Interflow Tank Container System Ltd.
column168: An overseas import tank container TMLU 624119 (type IM01/IM101) that was grounded in the intermodal parking lot after its arrival on an inbound BNSF intermodal train was reported dripping liquid from this tank container's bottom discharge valve area. TMLU 624119 was cordoned off within the intermodal parking lot. The local F.D. and a BNSF response contractor were called. Inspection of TMLU 624119 revealed that the dripping was from the bottom discharge butterfly valve's 3 inch BSP (British Standard Pipe) with closure cap. The four bolt flange of which the closure cap is attached had a loose bottom flange bolt nut which allowed a small amount of product captured between the discharge valve and the closure cap to leak. The flange bolt nut was tool tightened and the product drips ceased. The small amount of product that impacted the asphalt paving directly under the bottom discharge valve was cleaned. TMLU 624119 was out-gated from the intermodal facility on 10/29/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: HCC driver was loading 55 gal drum of paint waste onto back of box van truck with a dolly and the drum clip on the dolly failed to hold the drum and the drum tipped forward and slid off the lift gate.  When the drum hit the ground (asphalt only) the lid and ring came loose and the contents of the drum spilled onto the asphalt.  Absorbent was immediately placed around the spilled material.  The entire process from the spill to full clean up was approximately 4 hours.
column169: New drum carts have been ordered for the HCC Branch to ensure a proper securement to the cart in the future.  Employee re-training for drum handling has been done as well.

column168: Driver hooked up the hoses to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  Before he opened the valve on the customer tank, he opened trailer valve just a little to make sure there weren't any leaks on the discharge valve or hoses.  There was  small leak between 2 hose connections so the driver immedately closed the valve on the trailer.  He's not sure why it leaked.  There was a gasket in place and nothing looked unusual.  To err on the side of safety, he changed out both sections of hose and completed the unload without incident.
column169: The driver said he had the trailer valve opened just a little but he still should have had the valve open on the customer storage tank so it didn't build up pressure in the hose.  That may have played a part in the leak.

column168: 2 drivers transferring product from cargo tank to totes at a customer.  One driver by the trailer control and one manning the drumming nozzle in the tote.  There was a kink in the hose from moving from one tote to the next and the kink caused the drumming nozzle to jerk.  The driver lost control of it briefly and a little sprayed onto the concrete and top of tote.  None got on the driver.  He was wearing full PPE.
column169: The driver received performance enhance training after the incident.  Extra care needs to be taken when a drumming nozzle is used.

column168: Driver had used extra hose to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He was hooked up to a section of customer hose that went into the stoarge tank.  After completing the unload, the driver walked the hose to the customer fill line to try to empty the product in it.  Then the plant employee started to walk the hose and disconnect the sections as he went.  The driver put caps on the hoses.  When they got almost to the customer section of hose, about 1/2 gallon of product backflowed out of the hose.  The spill went into a containment area.
column169: Neither the driver nor the plant employee could offer an explanation of why it backflowed out.  Maybe just one person doing this would have been more careful.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering sodium hydroxide solution to a customer location. When the driver arrived at the site, the site terminal operator signed off on our product integrity form which lets the driver know that the product will fit. The tank at the client's site is housed inside a building. While finishing up the unloading process the driver thought he heard a splashing sound in the building. The driver immediately shut off the flow of product to investigate the sound. The driver finds that the tank had overfilled and approximately 5-10 gallons leaked onto the containment area around the tank. The terminal operator was called into the area and upon contacting the supplier and  investigating, it was determined that the driver had done nothing wrong and the customer would handle all clean-up associated with the leak.
column169: Customer was advised to check order before placing it to avoid any future overfills.

column168: While transferring containers to another trailer at the Veolia Sauget, IL intransit facility, the Veolia driver noticed that a drum containing mercury amalgam had leaked a small amount of elemental mercury. Upon further investigation, it was determined that the mercury leaked through a very small hole on the bottom of the drum that appeared to have been worn through by the material inside the container. In all other aspects, the container appeared to be of good integrity. The Veolia driver overpacked leaking drum, and cleaned up the spilled material, adding it to the overpack container.
column169: The spill incident was communicated to the generator of the material and they, along with the transporter, will ensure the containers being used in the future are in good condition and packed in a manner that the amalgam will not abrade the container.

column17: City of L.A. Dept. of Water & Power
column168: At approximately 1255 hours, we experienced a fluorosilicic acid (FSA) spill from a railcar connection at the Los Angeles Aqueduct Filtration Plant.  Water Treatment Operators were offloading FSA from the railcar to an onsite storage tank.   This process requires using air pressure, and when one of the operators manipulated the product hose, it disconnected and the railcar starting vented FSA out of the piping located on top of the car.  The Control Room Operator had all non-essential personnel clear the area and at approximately 1310 hours, while the Plant Engineer (Vee Miller) contacted 911 Emergency Services to report a HAZMAT incident with potentially injured employees.  The Control Room Operator notified Corporate Environmental Services, who subsequently made all appropriate notifications to appropriate agencies, including USEPA and CA OES.  DWP employees deployed containment devices and absorbent pillows to contain the spill within the railcar area and there were NO offsite releases of chemical.     Los Angeles Fire Department arrived on site at approximately 1330 hours, deployed their HAZMAT team, conducted decontamination procedures on affected Water Treatment personnel, and transported five DWP personnel to local hospitals as a precautionary measure.  Los Angeles Police Department and DWP Security Services personnel secured the LAAFP perimeter to keep out onlookers and non-essential personnel.  LAFD reported back on the extent of the contaminated area and turned the site back over to DWP and County Fire Department for HAZMAT cleanup at approximately 1545 hours.      At approximately 1600 hours three employees called the LAAFP and requested pickup at the hospital so they could return to the plant and collect their personal effects.  The hospital had examined the employees and released them without restrictions.  At approximately 1705 hours, the fourth employee was released from medical care after First Aid Treatment.  The fifth employee is had some respiratory damage and was hospitalized for three days.      At approximately 1630 hours, LAAFP personnel and DWP ISS Hazmat Cleanup personnel began work on securing equipment and cleaning up any remaining FSA in the area.  Please note that most of the FSA evaporated, while some soaked into the adjacent soil.  County Fire Department representatives were on site and approved of our approach to cleanup the spill.     Key Facts:    Spill of between 2500-3000 gallons of FSA.  Five employees sent to hospital.  Three released after examination, one given first aid and released, one hospitalized for three days due to respiratory damage.  Minor release to water way, but containment immediately undertaken and no damage to any environmentally sensitive areas.  Spill area fully contained with absorbent materials and all drainage channels dyked to prevent any offsite migration.    LAFD HAZMAT and LAPD responded on site to respond to the spill.  HAZMAT cleanup by DWP personnel in progress as approved by LA
column169: DWP investigation indicates an employee tried to adjust or remove 2-inch cam-lock connection in order to stop minor dripping leak of FSA even though the railcar was pressurized to 20-30 psi and approximately half-empty.  Other employees warned the employee in question not to manipulate the fitting; however, it appears he ignored their warnings.  Remedial actions will include potential disciplinary action, additional training and review of existing Standard Operating Procedures to determine if there are any deficiencies.  At this point, all mechanical equipment checks out and was in proper working order at the time of the incident.  Mechanical failure was not a root cause, rather a deliberate unsafe act by an employee led to the release.

THE HOLE IN PAIL APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY FORKLIFT BLADE, POSSIBLE BY FORKLIFT USED AT FIRST PICKUP STOP. YRCW CHEMICAL HELPLINE WAS CONTACTED AND DUE TO FLASHPOINT OF PAINT PRODUCT INVOLVED IT WAS DETERMINED IMMEDIATE CLEAN-UP REQUIRED BY EMERGENCY REPSONSE TEAM. YRC CONTACTED SWS 1ST REPSONSE AND THEY WENT TO SITE AND PERFORMED CLEAN-UP INSIDE OF OUR TRAILER AND MINIMAL AMOUNT THAT HAD LEAKED OUTSIDE OF TRAILER. THE CLEAN UP WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUM, MARKERD AND LABELED AND IS BEING HELD IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BAY AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSAL.

column169: USE CARE WHEN LOADING ANY HAZMAT, OR MAKE SURE SMALL PALLETS ARE PROPERLY BRACED. column168: A WOODEN CRATE CONTAINING A HOIST ASSEMBLY WAS RECEIVED AT OUR FACILITY ON 09/30/2008.  THIS SHIPMENT WENT THROUGH OUR NORMAL RECEIVING PROCESS. IMMEDIATELY THE EXPLOSIVE WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN AN EXPLOSIVECABINET.  DOCUMENTS AND CRATE WERE VERIFIED THAT THIS SHIPMENT CAME IN AS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT SHIPMENT.                                                                                                                                                  Attachments: 1) Roadway Express airway bill; 2) RMA(showing special instructions on returning Hazmat shipments); 3) 2 Photographs showing the unit with the explosive attached; 4) Notification letter

column169: REFRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING. REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALSI PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

On October 18, 2008, a Swift Transportation tractor-trailer was involved in an incident during which, a drum of product burst.  The release impacted an area inside the trailer and the asphalt under the tractor and trailer.  A contractor was dispatched to perform remediation and cleanup operations.    Upon arrival, the contractor coordinated with state police and established a 1000ft evacuation radius.  The contractor waited on site for technical assistance from the shipper's response team and for more equipment, supplies, and personnel to arrive.  They were instructed by the incident commander to decon and overpack all of the remaining drums in the load.  Using an ammonia solution, the contractor wiped down the exterior of the drums and examined them for damage or signs of failure.  The drums were then staged outside the trailer on visqueen.  Once all of the drums were removed from the trailer, the contractor began placing them into steel overpacks.  The inside of the trailer was decontaminated with the same ammonia solution.  Once the trailer was cleaned, the overpacked drums were reloaded into the trailer.  The contractor then focused decontamination efforts on the outside of the trailer, the tractor, and the asphalt parking surface.  Once all equipment was thoroughly cleaned, the trailer was sent back to the shipper's facility in Baytown, Texas.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHTWHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT  OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL. LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE  COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE WAS ISSUED WITH REVIEWS AND INSTRUCTIONS ON SAFE PROCEDURES REGARDING PROPER UNLOADING, LOADING AND HANDLING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND FREIGHT.

column168: Driver had just left our office terminal heading down two-lane road.  A container truck was coming in opposite direction and our driver thought the mirrors were going to hit.  Our driver moved over and went off the right shoulder.  Driver was caught with right side of tanker in the ditch while going down road.  Driver lost control and rolled over on the right shoulder.  Driver was not hurt in the incident. Emergency crews responded and we called an environmental crew to the scene.  We brought another tanker to the scene and pumped over the product. Truck and tanker were totalled.  Scene was cleaned up after 6 hours.
column169: We advocate the Smith System so we preached the importance to our drivers of staying focused and attentive.  We stressed the importance of getting sleep and rest when off duty and away from work.  We also focused on the hours of service and making sure we stay in compliance with all DOT regulations and requirements.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: Driver was heading east on Hwy-175 and as the highway splits with Hwy 310 it becomes a three-lane, 20mph turn that actually turns under Hwy 310.  The driver was traveling in the middle lane and, as he approached the sharp turn, he claimed to have had a right front tire blow-out and he lost control hitting the concrete barriers to the far right and rolling the tractor and tanker. The driver was knocked out and was pulled from the tractor by two unknown persons.  The tractor and tanker caught fire and burned to the ground.  The heat and fire damaged the underpass of Hwy 310 and had to be shutdown. Hwys 310 and 175, at their intersection, was shutdown and will continue to be shut down until repairs can be made to the overpass.  Basin Environmental was called out to handle cleanup duties and subcontracted Holtcher to do the labor.  Some of the fluid, a combination of fuel and water from the roll-over, entered a storm drain under the overpass and traveled to the storm water collection point. This has been cleaned to the satisfaction of TCEQ and is still being monitored by Basin.

column168: Driver loaded gasoline at the Motiva Terminal in Charleston, SC.  Load was to be delivered to Market Express in Matthews, SC.  Driver was in route on 1-77 North in Rock Hill, SC, when he took his eyes off the road.  When driver realized he was on the right shoulder, he over-reacted and jerked the wheel to the left. He crossed the lanes and into the medium.  At the time he lost control and had a rollover.  Driver was not hurt in the accident.  He called his dispatch and dispatch called the safety manager.  Safety Manager had an environmental team sent to the scene.  Troopers and Emergency Crew secured and helped clean up the scene.  We sent another tanker to the scene and we pumped over all the product.  Tanker and truck were totalled.  When truck rolled over the seal leaked in the fifth dome lid and that is where we lost our product, 17 gallons. Traffic was detained and slow for six hours.
column169: We advocate the Smith System so we preach the importance to our drivers of staying focused and attentive.  We stressed the importance of getting sleep and rest when off duty and away from work.  We also focused on the hours of service and making sure we stay in compliance with all DOT regulations and requirements.

A straight box truck arrived at a customer’s location to accept non-bulk packages for transportation to a licensed waste management facility.  During the loading operation, a fork-lift operator inadvertently punctured a container that had been previously loaded onto the vehicle.  The damage resulted in approximately 20 gallons of the acetone/methylene chloride mixture to escape from the truck onto the concrete parking area and into a drainage collection system.  Please note this drain was protected from allowing material to escape into the environment.  Facility personnel immediately stopped the loading operation and initiated clean-up and remediation activities.  These activities included making proper notifications to facility management and State environmental agencies.  In addition, representatives from Clean Harbors were notified and a formal response was initiated.  An emergency response team was dispatched to the site and proceeded to absorb all free liquids with a suitable absorbent material.  The damaged drum was placed into a suitable salvage container and secured for continuing transportation.  A vacuum truck was dispatched to remove all material and contaminated debris that was released into the drainage collection system.  In addition this drain was rinsed and flushed until direct monitoring equipment showed evidence of no residual contamination.  All clean-up debris and reside were containerized and sent for disposal to a fully licensed waste management facility.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence the individuals involved in the loading operation were retrained on Clean Harbor's Industrial Truck Guildeines that outline the proper use and operation of mechanical mandling equipment.  In additon, hazard awareness training was provided to ensure employees identify potential hazads/obstacles in their work areas.

column168: The driver of the CMV noticed a liquid product leaking from the underneath the trailer.  The carrier cordinated clean-up efforts with shipper and a professional celan-up crew was dispatched to the scene.  Upon arrival they reviewed bills for suspected leaking product and confirm safe entry into trailer.  After opening trailer, they wore appropriate personal protective equipment and entered, identifying that one 55 gallon barrel was leaking from the bottom.  The barrel had been placed on top of a wooden pallet and had freight stacked on top of it.  An unidentified object punctured the drum from the bottom causing a slow leakage that eventually covered about 6-7 feet of trailer floor surface.  The damaged drum was removed and repacked inside a larger secured container for continuation of trip to consignee.  The surface area of the trailer and bottom of trailer where leaking had occured was cleaned of residue before resuming trip.  There was minimal leakage that had fallen from trailer floor, but the ground was cleaned to eliminate residue.
column169: To prevent further incident, better attention should be provided by loading persons.  Items should be cleared underneath to prevent punture and there should be no additional stressed loaded on top of a hazardous material package.

column168: The Flying J Transportation (FJ) driver had moved over to the far left lane to allow for merging traffic to move into middle lane because the far right lane was an exit only lane.  FJ driver started to move back into middle lane when he clipped the car that he was unable to see.  This caused the car to spin out of control in front of the FJ truck.  FJ driver tried to slow down and avoid hitting car when he lost control and went into median and rolled over.
column169: Flying J has a safety committee review all accidents and it was determinedby the committee that this was a major preventable accident.  Because of this, the driver's employment with FJ was terminated.  FJ requires drivers to go through intense new hire training as well as recurring monthly training afterwards.  Each driver is trained in the Smith System Safe Driving System to help prevent accidents and change driving habits for the better.  We will continue to enhance training programs and develop new programs to help prevent these types of incidents in the future.

column168: A Remedial Action Completion Report summarizing the details of the incident is attached. SO I PROCESSED THE SCRUB SOAP AND THE CONTAMINATED FLAMMABLE LIQUID THROUGH THE DMP. THE SALVAGABLE PORTION IS BEING RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

column169: INSPECT TOTE WHEN PICKING UP. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. BUNGS, LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF A TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS ANDTOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAP LYCLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: Driver was unloading #2 diesel at Logan Ag in Griggsville Illinois. He was unloading part of the product into the wrong tank due to poor marking. The storage tank is not visible from the loading area. When the tank overflowed he was unaware since there is no overfill device or alarm and therefore there was a spill of 1016 gallons. Reports were filed within the hour with the DOT and Illinois Emergency Management Agency. R.L. Hoener and Co. of Quincy Ii was called in to deal with the clean up of the site. Dan Simmons, owner was on the scene within two hours and assessed the situation with the owner, Ed Logan and Marty Jackson of R.L. Hoener. Dan was able to record on video camera the set up at Logan Ag. Dan was on the scene two other times during this process of clean up. The clean up, as of today, November l9”, is still on going, but to be completed this week. The soil has been excavated to a depth where the contaminant is no longer present. The fmal report from Hoener’s will be filed as soon as the work is completed. Attached are the current materials concerning the spill as of today.
column169: We have completed additional training with our driver’s informing them of the situation of the new storage facility at Logan Ag. We have implored them to be aware of the correct tanks and the markings on the tank, as well as the fact that overfill devices and alarms are not present. We have also pointed out that the distance to the storage tanks is far enough away from the unloading area it is impossible to monitor the truck unloading and see the tanks at the same time.  Continued training in this area will be conducted with any new drivers that might come into our employ.

On October 2, 2008 a Quick Fuel Fleet Services driver overfilled an aboveground storage tank used to fuel an emergency generator. Approximately 37 gallons of diesel fuel was released inside a building on concrete. The fuel migrated outside of the building onto a concrete apron and then into surrounding soils. We contacted our Contractor Emergency Management Inc. who dispatched a response team (TAS Environmental)to the site. TAS Environmental employees cleaned up the free liquids on site and steam cleaned the concrete impacted surfaces. Impacted soils were dug from the site utilizing a small backhoe. Impacted soils and water were properly transported and disposed off site. Confirmatory samples were collected from the bottom of the excavation and analytical results revealed the site was fully remediated. Excavation was backfilled and restored to former condition.

column168: At 8:50 am our employee noticed propane vapor around the top of our 30,000 gallon w.c. storage tank after loading his bobtail delivery truck (CTMV).  It was determined that the liquid by-pass pipe return from the pump was leaking at a weld where the by-pass return pipe passed through the manway of the storage container.  Due to the configuration of the piping and associated valves, only the propane in the pump by-pass return piping was released and dispersed to the atmosphere - approximately 5 gallons.  Emergency response personnel were contacted and immediately dispatched.  Immediately upon arriving and systematically every 45 minutes thereafter, Emergency ResponsePersonnel used combustible gas detectors to check for levels of propane - none was ever detected.  Our transport division dispatched two transports to unload the storage tank, as a precautionary measure and to aid in the accessibility to our plant by Emergency Responders and our two transport vehicles to unload the storage tank.  At 9:30 am the roadway was closed to the general public. The closure lasted approximately 8 hours but was not done as a direct result of the hazardous material.  By 6:00 pm all liquid had been removed from the storage tank and the roadway re-opened.  At that time Highlands Millwright Company flared off remaining propane vapor pressure in storage tank.  Flaring was completed at midnight.  Repairs cost to the piping system and manway totaled $6289.60 (as indicated earlier) for parts and labor.

column168: At approximately 10:30 am, the EJ&E railroad locomotive entered EMCO property and made a connection to the appropriate railcars for the purpose of moving railcars around on our spur tracks.  As the locomotive backed onto the main railway from the spur, he stopped on the rail crossing on Martin Luther King Drive.  The stopping agitated the liquid in the railcars and splashed the liquid material inside the car against the top lid of the car and forced the lid open.  The locomotive immediately stopped movement of the cars while still across Martin Luther King Drive and resealed the top manhole of the railcar.  The estimated quantity of release was approximately 10 gallons of material. The release covered an area approximately 15 feet by 10 feet on the railway and road area. The area was impervious road and rail crossing mat.  An EMCO employee immediately began the cleanup utilizing absorbent pads to remove the spilled material from the impacted area.  The pads were properly contained/labeled and disposed of through an existing waste profile.  No reportable quantities of materials were exceeded and there were no injuries or exposures to the general public.  However, the incident was reported to IEMA, LEPC, and the North Chicago Fire/Hazardous Material Department for precautionary reasons because the spill impacted a public roadway.  It is believed the cause of the incident was due to human error.  The manhole on top of the car was opened the day before to collect a manual grab sample of the material for testing.  If the manhole was properly closed and secured/bolted, it would not have opened from the force of the splash.
column169: EMCO has implemented the following additional preventive measures to prevent any future occurrence of this incident:         1. All employees associated with loading and unloading railcars will be notified and will be retrained on the importance of re-sealing and bolting the manway access covers on the tops of railcars.                               2. In addition to inspecting the railcars for closed valves and disconnected hoses, EMCO employees will be required to inspect and ensure that all manholes are property closed and secured prior to lowering the blue STOPflag indicating the railcar's readiness to be moved.    These measures will be employed whether or not the railcar leaves our property, even if it is only for a railcar being switched from one siding track to another.

column168: Transport vehicle operated by TransWood Inc stopped on designated route at mandatory fuel stop. Truck drivers noticed a mist rising from the manifold cabinet at rear of trailer. Drivers located vehicle away from persons aspractical, notified dispatch of leak, and called 911, evacuated the vehicle with shipping documents and HM information. TransWood notified MEMO and PCS of leaking trailer. MEMC dispatched Eagle Environmental(contracted response) to the site. Police, fire and ambulance responded TransWood personnel were not allowed inthe area to record events or gather information, and the site was handled upon arrival by Eagle Environmental andPreston Summers from LA Hazmat who was acting Incident Commander.MEMC indicates the following causes of failure:1) Leak through #3 tube block valve2) Defective air operated valve failed to hold the manifold tube closed3) Loose threads on hose cap prevented hose cap from sealing Estimated 10 Ibs of material to atmosphere.Gas was leaking out of the manifold capped hose connection. Leak path was out of #3 block valve, then past main unload valve, and out capped hose connection. MEMC responder cycled the #3 tube valve and leak stopped.Manifold was evacuated and trailer released.

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 10/27/08, PSC TRAILER NO. 966 WAS PICKED UP FROM PSC TANK WASH FACILITY IN BATON ROUGE, LA AND DELIVERED TO FERRO CORPORATION IN ZACHARY, LA.  THE TRAILER WAS DOLLIED DOWN AT FERRO TO BE LOADED BY FERRO PERSONNEL FOR TRANSPORT TO RHODIA, INC. IN BATON ROUGE, LA.  ON THE MORNING OF 10/28/08, THE LOADED TANK WAS PICKED UP AT FERRO AND TRANSPORTED TO PHODIA ARRIVING AT APPROX. 5:45AM.  UPON ARRIVAL IT WAS NOTICED THAT LIQUID AND LEAKED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER FROM THE TOP FRONT WASHOUT CAP, WHICH WAS HANGING LOOSE BY ITS RETAINING CABLE.  FERRO PERSONNEL WERE CALLED TO RHODIA WHERE HE RESECURED THE CAP.  THE TRAILER WAS LEFT AT PHODIA FOR UNLOADING AND PICKED UP EMPTY ON 10/30/08.  THE EXACT QUANTITY OF THE RELEASE IS NOT KNOWN, BUT WAS ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN 60 LBS.  BY COMPARING OUTBOUND FERRO SCALE WEIGHT TO INBOUND RHODIA SCALE WEIGHT.  THE RELEASE DURATION IS NOT KNOWN BECAUSE IT CANNOT BE DETERMINED WHEN THE WASHOUT CAP CAME LOOSE, SINCE IT WAS REORTED TO BE IN PLACE UPON LEAVING FERRO.  HOWEVER, THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE DID NOT EXCEED 45 MINUTES BECAUSE THAT WAS THE TRAVEL TIME FROM DEPARTURE FROM FERRO TO ARRIVAL AT RHODIA.
column169: EMPHASIS WILL BE STRESSED WITH DRIVERS TO ASSURE THAT ALL TANK CONNECTIONS ARE SECURE WHEN PICKING UP EMPTY TANKS FROM TANK WASH FACILITIES AND WHEN PICKING UP LOADED TANKS FROM SHIPPERS' FACILITIES, AND DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED NOT TO HOOK UP TO A TRAILER UNLESS THEY CAN VERIFY THAT ALL CONNECTIONS ARE SECURE.  INCREASED EMPHASIS BY THE REGULATING AGENCIES WITH TANK WASH FACILITIES AND SHIPPERS REGARDING THE NECESSITY FOR SECURE CONNECTIONS COULD BE VERY HELPFUL, SINCE DRIVERS ARE RARELY, IF EVER, INVOLVED IN EITHER THE CLEANING OF TANKS OR THE LOADING OF TANKS AND THEY HAVE NO "SAFE" ACCESS TO THE TOPS OF TANKS UNLESS THEY ARE LOCATED AT LOADING RACKS OR CLEANING RACKS.

UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING A FUEL ODOR. THEY  REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A FUEL CONTROL UNIT WITH FUEL STILL INSIDE. DUE TO NO POSITIVE MEANS OF CLOSURE AND THE SHIPMENT NOT BEING PROPERLY DRAINED/PREPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF 4 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT # 412, N784AX. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION.THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAR OF SCENE: 0351.THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE ON SOUTH SEA LOOP AND DISCOVERED 1 FUEL INJECTOR LEAKING APPROX. 1 OUNCE OF DIESEL FUEL FROM ITS VALVE. HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION.
column169: CUSTOMER FOLLOWUP

column168: PACKAGE WAS SENT THROUGH THE SORT WHERE IT STARTED LEAKING. LATER INVESTIGATION DISCOVED THIS WAS BECAUSE THE CAP AND POPPED OF THE COTAINER OF RUBBING ALCOHOL. PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED AND FIRST RESPONDER CLEANED UP SPILLIAGE FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEGURES.
column169: 1 GALLON JUG OF RUBING ALCOHOL HAD NO SECONDARY SEAL UNDER THE CAP. WITH A SEAL THE CAP MAY OF NOT COME OFF AND/OR LEAKAGE WOULD OF NOT OCCURED.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE INBOUND SORTING OPERATION.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT 2 PLASTIC BOTTLES OF SOME UNKNOWN CLEANING SOLUTION HAD SPILLED INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  ALSO IN THE PACKAGE WERE TWO AEROSOL CANS, BUT DUE TO THE SPILL THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO READ THE CONTAINER TO SEE WHETHER THE PRODUCT WAS FLAMMABLE OR NON FLAMMABLE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION WITH THE FAA.  I CONTACTED THE EWR/FAA OFFICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT, AND SUBMITTED INFORMATION TO RYAN POHLKE AT 15:45 ON WEDNESDAY OCT. 15, 2008.  I ALSO SENT PHOTOS OT THE INCIDENT TO HIM, AND HE STATED TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING HIS REVIEW.  THE SHIPMENT IS CONTINUING TO BE HELD, AND WILL EITHER BE DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE OR HAVE THE CONSIGNEE PICK IT UP FROM OUR OFFICE, ONCE THE FAA FINISHES THEIR REVIEW.

The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

The package was dropped in handling.  Examination of the inner container revealed a ruptured seam which allowed the contents to escape. The leakage was contained.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
